TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding Voluntary Turnover: Path-Specific Job Satisfaction Effects and The Importance of Unsolicited Job Offers
AU  - Lee, Tae Heon
AU  - Gerhart, Barry
AU  - Weller, Ingo
AU  - Trevor, Charlie O.
Y1  - 2008/08/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.33665124
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.33665124
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 651
EP  - 671
VL  - 51
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In response to traditional approaches' limited success in explaining voluntary turnover, we explored a paradigmatic shift in turnover research. Using a large national sample, we found we could more successfully model voluntary turnover by recognizing that job (dis)satisfaction and ease of movement importance depend on the group of leavers being studied. For example, ongoing job satisfaction had smaller effects for turnover driven by certain shocks (unsolicited job offers and family-related reasons), which accounted for 40 percent of all quits. Moreover, the prevalence of unsolicited job offers may necessitate rethinking the role of ease of movement in turnover decisions.
AB  - In response to traditional approaches' limited success in explaining voluntary turnover, we explored a paradigmatic shift in turnover research. Using a large national sample, we found we could more successfully model voluntary turnover by recognizing that job (dis)satisfaction and ease of movement importance depend on the group of leavers being studied. For example, ongoing job satisfaction had smaller effects for turnover driven by certain shocks (unsolicited job offers and family-related reasons), which accounted for 40 percent of all quits. Moreover, the prevalence of unsolicited job offers may necessitate rethinking the role of ease of movement in turnover decisions.
