TY  - JOUR
T1  - Reducing Causal Ambiguity In Acquisition Integration: Intermediate Goals As Mediators OfIntegration Decisions and Acquisition Performance
AU  - Cording, Margaret
AU  - Christmann, Petra
AU  - King, David R.
Y1  - 2008/08/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.33665279
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.33665279
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 744
EP  - 767
VL  - 51
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Integration is a difficult process, but one that is vital to acquisition performance. One reason acquirers encounter difficulties is that the integration process exhibits high levels of intrafirm linkage ambiguity?a lack of clarity in the causal link between integration decisions and their performance outcomes. We introduce the construct of intermediate goals as a mechanism that reduces intrafirm linkage ambiguity. Our structural model results, based on a sample of 129 horizontal acquisitions, indicate that the achievement of two intermediate goals (internal reorganization and market expansion) fully mediates the relationships between four integration decisions and acquisition performance.
AB  - Integration is a difficult process, but one that is vital to acquisition performance. One reason acquirers encounter difficulties is that the integration process exhibits high levels of intrafirm linkage ambiguity?a lack of clarity in the causal link between integration decisions and their performance outcomes. We introduce the construct of intermediate goals as a mechanism that reduces intrafirm linkage ambiguity. Our structural model results, based on a sample of 129 horizontal acquisitions, indicate that the achievement of two intermediate goals (internal reorganization and market expansion) fully mediates the relationships between four integration decisions and acquisition performance.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.33665279
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2008.33665279
